THE RESPONSE
These survey results have presented advocates of current policies with a clear dilemma-how could the present approach be a success in the face of the most basic evidence indicating otherwise? The response by advocates of school-based prevention programs has focused on two issues: First, it is argued that drug use and accompanying favorable attitudes have increased among young people as the financial commitment by federal government to drug prevention has declined; and second, it is argued that these problems have become worse because the right types of prevention programs are not being supported.
